<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Ha Giang Loop</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Ha Giang Loop</h2><p><i>Northern Vietnam · Ha Giang to Dong Van to Meo Vac and back</i></p><p><b>350 km of karst mountains and switchbacks in Vietnam's far north — the country's most spectacular drive.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>167 km (104 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 days minimum (motorbike or self-drive)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>September–November (dry, cool) and March (buckwheat blossom)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Steep drops on the Ma Pi Leng pass, rain makes mountain roads dangerous, frequent fog, livestock on road, motorbike accidents are common (rent helmets, ride sober)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>443</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Dong Van Karst Plateau is a UNESCO Global Geopark of limestone peaks, hidden valleys, and ethnic-minority villages — Hmong, Tay, Dao, Lo Lo. The loop circles the plateau from Ha Giang town. The dramatic climax is the Ma Pi Leng Pass between Dong Van and Meo Vac — a road blasted into the side of a 1,500 m gorge above the Nho Que River, often called Vietnam's most beautiful road. Travelers traditionally rent a motorbike or hire an 'easy rider' (a local who drives while you ride pillion). Lung Cu, the country's northernmost point, has a flag tower marking the border with China visible on the next ridge. Markets in the small towns on Sunday morning are a riot of indigo cloth and silver jewellery.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Quan Ba — Twin Mountains</b> — Two perfect symmetric karst hills called the 'Fairy Twin Mountains' in local legend. View from the Heaven Gate pass on the climb up from Tam Son.</li><li><b>Sung La valley</b> — Tucked Hmong village known for indigo dyeing and the H'mong King's Palace nearby — a 1903 stone-and-pomelo-wood compound built for a Hmong opium-trade ruler. Tile-roofed houses with stone fences.</li><li><b>Dong Van old town</b> — 100-year-old market square with French-colonial-influenced Hmong architecture. Sunday morning market is the highlight — produce, textiles, livestock, and hot bowls of thắng cố (horse-meat soup) on the steps.</li><li><b>Lung Cu flag tower</b> — Vietnam's northernmost point. 33 m tower; 839 steps up; a 54 m² national flag (one for each of Vietnam's recognized ethnic groups) snaps in the wind. China's mountains rise on the next ridge.</li><li><b>Ma Pi Leng Pass</b> — 1,500 m above the emerald Nho Que River. A controversial roadside hotel built in 2018 was forced to demolish part of its structure. Pull off at the official viewpoint; boats run river tours from below.</li><li><b>Meo Vac</b> — Sunday market town. Tho Ha valley below. The road from here back to Yen Minh climbs over the equally spectacular Mau Due Pass.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
