<Folder><name>Scenic Points</name><Placemark><name>Quan Ba — Twin Mountains</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Two perfect symmetric karst hills called the 'Fairy Twin Mountains' in local legend. View from the Heaven Gate pass on the climb up from Tam Son.]]></description><Point><coordinates>105.028300,23.073600,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Sung La valley</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Tucked Hmong village known for indigo dyeing and the H'mong King's Palace nearby — a 1903 stone-and-pomelo-wood compound built for a Hmong opium-trade ruler. Tile-roofed houses with stone fences.]]></description><Point><coordinates>105.323600,23.229700,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Dong Van old town</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[100-year-old market square with French-colonial-influenced Hmong architecture. Sunday morning market is the highlight — produce, textiles, livestock, and hot bowls of thắng cố (horse-meat soup) on the steps.]]></description><Point><coordinates>105.362200,23.276700,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Lung Cu flag tower</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Vietnam's northernmost point. 33 m tower; 839 steps up; a 54 m² national flag (one for each of Vietnam's recognized ethnic groups) snaps in the wind. China's mountains rise on the next ridge.]]></description><Point><coordinates>105.322500,23.371900,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Ma Pi Leng Pass</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[1,500 m above the emerald Nho Que River. A controversial roadside hotel built in 2018 was forced to demolish part of its structure. Pull off at the official viewpoint; boats run river tours from below.]]></description><Point><coordinates>105.370000,23.284700,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Meo Vac</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Sunday market town. Tho Ha valley below. 